# Contact form → Telegram
#
# Copy to .env.local (gitignored via *.local) and fill in your own values.
# Never commit real values to this file.
#
#   1. Telegram → @BotFather → /newbot
#        name:     Portfolio-Bha3
#        username: anything ending in "bot", e.g. portfolio_bha3_bot
#      BotFather replies with the token.
#
#   2. Send your new bot any message (e.g. /start) so a chat exists.
#
#   3. Open this in a browser, swapping in your token:
#        https://api.telegram.org/bot<TOKEN>/getUpdates
#      Read result[0].message.chat.id — that's your chat id.
#
# WARNING: VITE_* values are inlined into the JS bundle at build time. This
# token is PUBLIC on the deployed site — anyone can read it in devtools. That's
# inherent to calling the Bot API from the browser; a bot token can't be scoped
# to an origin. If it's abused, revoke it in @BotFather, issue a new one and
# redeploy. Don't reuse this bot for anything that matters.

# NOTE: this file is COMMITTED to the public repo — placeholders only.
# Real values go in .env.local (gitignored). Never here.
#
# CHAT_ID is *your* Telegram user id (from @userinfobot), NOT the number before
# the colon in the token — that one is the bot's own id, and pointing the bot at
# itself fails with "chat not found".
VITE_TELEGRAM_BOT_TOKEN=123456789:AAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAA
VITE_TELEGRAM_CHAT_ID=987654321
